\f2\b\fs28 \cf0 Tone matters: how to sound helpful, not pushy\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Let\'92s be real\'97nobody enjoys being reminded about overdue payments. That\'92s why the tone of your dunning email is so important. It can either strengthen your customer relationship or make someone hit "unsubscribe" faster than you can say \'93insufficient funds.\'94\
\pard\pardeftab720\li800\fi-800\ri800\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \uc0\u55357 \u56481  So how do you strike the right tone? Be human. Be empathetic. Use language that acknowledges life happens\'97because it does! Maybe their credit card expired, or there was a billing issue on your end. Either way, this isn\'92t about blame\'97it\'92s about working together to fix the problem.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 A successful dunning email feels like a gentle nudge, not a legal threat. Avoid harsh language, and instead use clear, positive copy that shows you're here to help. The result? Fewer canceled subscriptions, fewer angry replies, and a whole lot more recovered payments.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs28 \cf0 Include the customer\'92s payment details to reduce friction\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Want to make it easy for your customer to resolve a failed payment? Show them exactly what\'92s going on. Including the customer's payment details\'97like the last four digits of their credit card, the outstanding balance, or the invoice number\'97removes guesswork and builds trust.\
This is especially important for subscription companies dealing with large customer accounts or multiple payment methods. You want the user to immediately recognize the issue and know what action to take.\
Just be sure to balance clarity with privacy. While payment information is helpful, sensitive data should be handled carefully\'97especially in B2B contexts. Still, the more relevant and accurate your details are, the smoother your payment recovery process will be.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs28 \cf0 Make the call to action crystal clear\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Your call to action is the star of the show\'97don\'92t let it blend into the background. Whether you\'92re reminding customers about an outstanding payment or giving a final notice before service suspension, the CTA should be easy to spot and even easier to click.\
Use clear, actionable language like \'93Update your payment method\'94 or \'93Pay your outstanding invoice.\'94 Avoid vague CTAs like \'93Click here\'94\'97they don\'92t inspire confidence. And if possible, deep link directly to the payment page so users can resolve the issue without hunting through their dashboard.\
Design matters too. Make your CTA a button in a standout color, and don\'92t be afraid to repeat it once or twice in longer emails. The goal is simple: reduce friction and encourage prompt attention.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs28 \cf0 Be upfront about the due date and consequences\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 When payment issues arise, clarity is your best friend. Always state the due date clearly in your dunning messages so customers know exactly when action is required. This helps set expectations and gives people time to act before things escalate.\
You should also be transparent about what happens if the payment isn\'92t resolved. Will their account be paused? Will they lose access to key features? Let them know\'97without being scary about it.\
Framing it as a heads-up, not a threat, helps maintain a positive customer relationship. You\'92re not just trying to collect money\'97you\'92re trying to help them avoid service interruption and keep their subscription active. It\'92s a win-win.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs36 \cf0 8 dunning email examples\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 When I recently changed my business card, I suddenly found myself on the receiving end of several dunning emails. It was a crash course in how different companies handle failed payments\'97and let me tell you, some did it 
\f1\i way
\f0\i0  better than others. Here are eight real-life examples worth studying.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs28 \cf0 Webflow\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Webflow sent me two dunning emails\'85 
\f1\i one minute apart
\f0\i0 . While both were clear and well-written, sending them so close together felt more like a glitch than a strategy.\
The first emphasized urgency with \'93Your sites are at risk!\'94\'97a bold subject line\'97but the second was more detailed, including my credit card\'92s last four digits and explaining what would happen if I didn\'92t update my billing information.\
The messaging was strong, but timing missteps like this can make automated dunning emails feel robotic. A little spacing between reminders could go a long way in improving customer communication.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
